"PERFACILE FACTU esse illis probat conata perficere, propterea quod ipse suae civitatis imperium obtenturus esset:  non esse dubium quin totius galliae plurimum helvetii possent; se suis copiis suoque exercitu illis regna conciliaturum confirmat."|"perfacile factu esse *** perficere, (he proves to them) that to accomplish their attempts was a very easy thing to do. The student meets for the first time the so-called supine. This term is a comparatively recent one to apply to this formation alone. In the Latin grammarians the word included both *** gerunds*** and ***supines.*** The student should bear in mind that the supine is nothing more than a verbal noun. The work done by this can be done by verbal nouns of any declension. The cases in common use are the accusative and ablative, although the dative appears rarely."

