"NOT FOUND"|"2. quid *** auderent, periclitabatur, he strove to ascertain what the enemy could do by their valor and what our men dared (to do). Tliis can be renderpd also, the valor of the enemy and the daring of our men. The Latin,Original fromHARVARD UNIVERSITY[book ilunlike the English, avoids the use of abstract nouns. In fact there are few such nouns that have equivalents in Latin. Either concrete nouns are preferred, e.g. a pueris, from boyhood, or a clause, e.g. permulta audent, great was their daring. See Hints for Translating, pp. 326-26."

