"NOT FOUND"|"Ablative Proper. The true ablative, as its name implies, is the case denoting separation. When we read suis finibus eos prohibent, we meet with a true ablative. All verbs of separation and oftentimes such adjectives as vacuus, liber, take the ablative proper."

