"ita sine ullo periculo tantam eorum multitudinem nostri interfecerunt quantum fuit diei spatium; SUB OCCASUM solis sequi destiterunt seque in castra, ut erat imperatum, receperunt."|"sub occasum, about sunset. The same difference that in has with the accusative and ablative is observed by sub. With the accusative sub has a vagueness of meaning, e.g. Livy, xxi. 16, sub idem tempus, about that same time (either before or after). In Livy, xxi. 18, sub hanc orationem, sub = after; but in xxi. 57, sub lucem, sub = before."

