"NOT FOUND"|"deinceps = almost an adjective continuis, successively, one after another. Compare v. 40, reliquis deinceps diebus, and Civil War, ili. 60, omnibus deinceps diebus. The adverb is inserted between the adjective and the noun as if in imitation of the Greek idiom which places an adverb between the article and the noun with the force of an adjective; e.g. 4 the present generation *** is in Greek * the now men.*** For this adjective force of the adverb in an English derivative, see the word peninsula (paene -f insula)."

