"NOT FOUND"|"Source gives cause or motive; e.g. qua de causa Helvetii *** praecedunt means that the excellence of the Helvetians came from that cause. The 44 ablative of cause *** is a historical ablative, although often the idea of instrument is strong; e.g. regni cupiditate inductus. The ablative which follows a comparative is a true ablative of separation. If we read Caesar fortior Pompeio, Caesar is braver than Pompey, the ablative means that Caesar is separated from Pom- pey by certain degrees of bravery. This same idea is expressed by such prepositions as prae, ante, etc. The prepositions with the ablative proper are a, ab, de, ex, pro, prae, sine, as well as those adverbs which later became prepositions, tenus, palam."

